'''Senhor''', from the Latin ''senior'' (comparative of ''senex'', "old man"), is the Portuguese word for (a feudal) Lord or [[Sir]] (sir has the same etymology). 

However it may also be used as a formal honorific, attached to certain titles, e.g. to a class in an [[order of knighthood]], as was the case in the empire of Brazil with the second class (of only three), styled Dignitary, of the Imperial Order of the Southern Cross (also enjoying the military honours of a [[Brigadier general]]), and with the second and third class (of six), styled Grand Dignitary viz. Dignitary, of the Order of the Rose.

